<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The member nc_param->value.str is used only for read-only accesses (checked against NULL, assigned to a const char * and passed to functions taking const char *). However the underlying struct member is defined as a non-const pointer (char *). Even though nc_param points to a const containing struct (so the pointer member itself becomes top-level const when accessed), the pointer's target is not const-qualified. Per MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 the pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible; here it is possible (functions like MHD_str_unquote and MHD_strx_to_uint64_n_ take const char *), so value.str should be declared as const char * (e.g. in struct _MHD_str_w_len).
</scenario>
